veryday practices and their relationship to larger social issues through an in-depth analysis of a trans-platform network of black American digital and social media users and content creators. In the crucial years leading up to the emergence of the Movement for Black Lives, black Americans used digital networks not only to cope with day-to-day experiences of racism, but also as an incubator for the debates that have since exploded onto the national stage. Beyond Hashtags tells the story of an influential subsection of these networks, an assemblage of podcasting, independent media, Instagram, Vine, Facebook, and the network of Twitter users that has come to be known as “Black Twitter.” Florini looks at how black Americans use these technologies often simultaneously to create a space to reassert their racial identities, forge community, organize politically, and create alternative media representations and news sources. Beyond Hashtags demonstrates how much insight marginalized users have into technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican American mass media. 0aAfrican Americans and mass media. 0aRace in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh  a2016 US presidential election.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aBlack Twitter.  aBlack cultural production.  aBlack enclaves.  aBlack innovation.  aBlack social spaces.  aFerguson.  aMartin Luther King Jr.  aMike Brown.  aThis Week in Blackness.  aTrayvon Martin.  aZimmerman.  aaffordances.  aalternative media production.  aanti-Black racism.  acitizen journalism.  acollective grieving.  acolorblindness.  acounterpublics.  adigital technology.  ahistorical narrative.  aindependent media production.  amainstream legacy media.  amedia narratives.  amonetization.  aneoliberal.  aneoliberalism.  aosci